What's in my soul?

773
00:50:43,116 --> 00:50:45,117
Feel my aura.

774
00:50:45,785 --> 00:50:47,703
I don't think I'm allowed to.

775
00:50:48,955 --> 00:50:52,041
Tell you what. Let's try it again.

776
00:50:52,625 --> 00:50:54,001
Hold hands.

777
00:50:56,838 --> 00:50:59,465
Gramoo once had a hangnail on her big toe.

778
00:50:59,549 --> 00:51:02,092
It got infected and traveled
to her vocal cords.

779
00:51:02,302 --> 00:51:03,926
Ruined her singing voice.

780
00:51:04,011 --> 00:51:06,304
I don't think Gramoo thought
it was insignificant.

781
00:52:05,071 --> 00:52:06,696
And some lettuce.

782
00:52:08,658 --> 00:52:11,201
Watch out for the rust when you get lettuce.

783
00:52:12,036 --> 00:52:13,078
Hey!

784
00:52:14,413 --> 00:52:16,039
I thought I recognized you two.

785
00:52:16,541 --> 00:52:18,542
- Hi, Vada.
- Hi.

786
00:52:20,419 --> 00:52:23,358
- We were picking things up for
the barbecue. - Yeah, me, too.

787
00:52:23,537 --> 00:52:25,311
Mind if I tag along?

788
00:52:25,346 --> 00:52:26,675
Not at all.

789
00:52:27,426 --> 00:52:31,929
- A lot of potatoes.
- It's for Shelly's famous potato salad.

790
00:52:32,222 --> 00:52:33,556
I'm looking forward to that.

791
00:52:33,640 --> 00:52:35,391
Hey! Damn it!

792
00:52:35,559 --> 00:52:38,602
- Vada, watch what you're doing.
- Sorry.

793
00:52:40,605 --> 00:52:42,982
You know, this is gonna be
my first Fourth of July picnic.

794
00:52:43,066 --> 00:52:44,108
Really?

795
00:52:44,192 --> 00:52:47,444
Dad, didn't you say
you needed prunes real bad?

796
00:52:47,529 --> 00:52:51,073
Vada, just put anything you
want in the cart, anything at all.

797
00:52:51,908 --> 00:52:54,702
I don't know what's gotten into her today.

798
00:52:55,036 --> 00:52:57,037
I need olives.

799
00:52:57,747 --> 00:53:02,042
I used to like my Ken and Barbie dolls.
Ken was my favorite.

800
00:53:02,127 --> 00:53:03,836
Then one Christmas, I got them a camper

801
00:53:03,920 --> 00:53:06,672
and all they wanted to do
was hang out in it by themselves.

802
00:53:06,756 --> 00:53:10,426
So I wasn't too upset when they took that
wrong turn and went over a cliff.

803
00:53:11,043 --> 00:53:14,944
<i>Gave proof through the night</i>

804
00:53:15,013 --> 00:53:19,040
<i>That our flag was still there</i>

805
00:53:19,117 --> 00:53:23,952
<i>Oh, say does that star-spangled</i>

806
00:53:24,022 --> 00:53:28,618
<i>Banner yet wave</i>

807
00:53:53,093 --> 00:53:56,054
Harry, Harry, Harry, Harry, Harry, Harry.

808
00:53:56,138 --> 00:53:58,931
I told you to use fewer briquettes
and now look what you've done.

809
00:53:59,015 --> 00:54:02,392
- You've cremated them.
- That's what I do.

810
00:54:02,727 --> 00:54:04,019
- You want to do it?
- No, no, no.

811
00:54:04,103 --> 00:54:05,354
If you think you know how,

812
00:54:05,438 --> 00:54:07,272
why don't you pre-measure
the briquettes into little packages?

813
00:54:07,357 --> 00:54:09,524
Put out a product. Support me for a while.

814
00:54:09,609 --> 00:54:12,027
- How's it going, chef?
- Okay.

815
00:54:12,111 --> 00:54:14,196
- I love your apron.
- Thanks.

816
00:54:14,656 --> 00:54:17,866
- Are they ready yet?
- No, sweetie, not yet.

817
00:54:17,951 --> 00:54:20,410
- When?
- Soon, honey, soon.

818
00:54:20,495 --> 00:54:21,536
When?

819
00:54:21,621 --> 00:54:24,498
In a minute. Look, it's hot.
Sweetie, you'll burn your nose.

820
00:54:24,582 --> 00:54:25,707
Look out.

821
00:54:39,514 --> 00:54:43,849
Rub-a-dub-dub. Thanks for the grub.
Yay, God.

822
00:54:43,934 --> 00:54:45,559
I'll second that.

823
00:54:45,894 --> 00:54:47,019
Hey, Shelly, like seafood?

824
00:54:47,354 --> 00:54:48,479
Why?

825
00:54:49,022 --> 00:54:50,273
See food.

826
00:54:50,607 --> 00:54:52,525
That's attractive.

827
00:54:55,070 --> 00:54:56,195
Shit!

828
00:54:56,530 --> 00:54:57,863
Excuse me.

829
00:55:01,243 --> 00:55:03,786
Hey, Shelly.
Who lives here, The Addams Family?

830
00:55:03,870 --> 00:55:05,329
Danny, what are you doing here?

831
00:55:05,414 --> 00:55:07,290
What am I doing here? What am I doing here?

832
00:55:07,374 --> 00:55:08,708
Hi, Ralph.

833
00:55:08,792 --> 00:55:12,003
- Danny, how did you find me?
- You told everybody where you were going.

834
00:55:12,087 --> 00:55:14,255
- I'm here for the motor home.
- No!

835
00:55:14,339 --> 00:55:17,133
These two people
do not have a good relationship.

836
00:55:17,384 --> 00:55:19,969
I've been living in it for over a year.
The camper is mine.

837
00:55:20,053 --> 00:55:22,305
Excuse me. "Mutual asset. "
That's what the lawyer said.

838
00:55:22,389 --> 00:55:25,974
It's supposed to be our mutual asset,
not Shelly's recreational vehicle.

839
00:55:26,058 --> 00:55:27,225
- Give me the keys.
- Keep your voice down...

840
00:55:27,310 --> 00:55:29,144
- Why?
- My boss is watching us.

841
00:55:29,228 --> 00:55:30,729
I'm impressed.

842
00:55:31,731 --> 00:55:34,983
- God, I guess I have to introduce you now.
- Yeah, all right.

843
00:55:38,195 --> 00:55:42,032
This is Harry, Phil,
Gramoo and Vada Sultenfuss.

844
00:55:42,116 --> 00:55:43,742
Vada Sultenfuss?

845
00:55:44,410 --> 00:55:45,410
Tough break.

846
00:55:45,661 --> 00:55:47,162
I like my name.

847
00:55:47,413 --> 00:55:52,083
This is Danny and Ralph.
They own the Dino Raphael salon in Detroit.

848
00:55:52,585 --> 00:55:53,585
We used to be married.

849
00:55:53,878 --> 00:55:55,587
Are you here to take Shelly back?

850
00:55:55,838 --> 00:55:57,047
Nice to meet you.

851
00:55:57,590 --> 00:56:01,259
We got burgers and hot dogs here
if you care to join us.

852
00:56:01,344 --> 00:56:05,889
- I can't stay. I'm here because my wife...
- Ex! Ex. Ex.

853
00:56:06,098 --> 00:56:09,099
My ex-wife seems
to have ripped off my camper.

854
00:56:09,267 --> 00:56:10,309
Shelly?

855
00:56:10,435 --> 00:56:13,354
Honestly, Harry, he got the Mustang.
I promise...

856
00:56:13,438 --> 00:56:16,565
I don't think so. In fact, I've got a copy
of the property settlement right here.

857
00:56:16,649 --> 00:56:19,276
Shit! This is my lease.

858
00:56:20,028 --> 00:56:22,863
Damn it, I keep forgetting things.
I'm getting senile.

859
00:56:23,281 --> 00:56:24,698
- Danny?
- What?

860
00:56:25,992 --> 00:56:29,161
Okay, I know you've suffered a terrible loss

861
00:56:29,245 --> 00:56:32,206
and there's really nothing
anyone can do to comfort you.

862
00:56:32,290 --> 00:56:36,460
But I urge you to focus
on the times you had with the camper.

863
00:56:36,961 --> 00:56:39,463
The trips you took, the sights you saw.

864
00:56:39,547 --> 00:56:42,132
Those days are gone now,
but they'll live on in your heart forever.

865
00:56:43,426 --> 00:56:44,551
Is this guy boinking you?

866
00:56:44,969 --> 00:56:47,596
That's a real bonehead thing to say!

867
00:56:48,348 --> 00:56:50,139
Look, you're not going
to take Shelly's camper.

868
00:56:50,265 --> 00:56:51,474
No?

869
00:56:51,558 --> 00:56:55,353
- It's her home. It's where she lives.
- Oh, really? Okay, fine. Look, go cook.

870
00:56:55,437 --> 00:56:56,813
Give me the goddamn keys.

871
00:56:56,897 --> 00:56:58,356
- Stop that, that hurts!
- Come on.

872
00:56:58,440 --> 00:57:00,191
Danny!

873
00:57:00,818 --> 00:57:02,318
What did you do that for?

874
00:57:02,403 --> 00:57:04,570
- Who are you?
- I'm his brother.

875
00:57:04,988 --> 00:57:08,116
Then you'll probably be visiting us here
quite often.

876
00:57:08,242 --> 00:57:09,242
Why?

877
00:57:09,743 --> 00:57:11,869
Because if he ever tries
to take Shelly's camper again,

878
00:57:11,954 --> 00:57:14,580
I'm going to bury him in my front yard.

879
00:57:18,836 --> 00:57:20,753
Your father's a savage.

880
00:57:23,715 --> 00:57:25,091
Bye, Ralph.

881
00:57:30,305 --> 00:57:32,890
Well, you were pretty great.

882
00:57:33,433 --> 00:57:35,183
Is it really your camper?

883
00:57:40,523 --> 00:57:42,149
Look!

884
00:57:45,862 --> 00:57:49,948
- Can you see them from the backyard?
- You can get the general idea.

885
00:57:53,536 --> 00:57:58,165
Yeah, there they are.
They always look the same every year.

886
00:57:59,041 --> 00:58:00,167
Look.

887
00:58:04,046 --> 00:58:05,547
Did you

888
00:58:06,132 --> 00:58:07,382
love him?

889
00:58:10,970 --> 00:58:13,430
I would never marry anybody I didn't love.

890
00:58:16,892 --> 00:58:18,684
He must like Shelly.

891
00:58:19,060 --> 00:58:21,729
I never saw him hit anyone in his life.

892
00:58:22,814 --> 00:58:24,356
He likes her.

893
00:58:25,984 --> 00:58:27,693
Does he love her?

894
00:58:28,695 --> 00:58:29,945
Probably.

895
00:58:32,491 --> 00:58:34,325
Do you like her?

896
00:58:34,576 --> 00:58:35,868
Yes, I do.

897
00:58:36,953 --> 00:58:40,581
- And I think she's very
good for your father. - Why?

898
00:58:42,083 --> 00:58:45,169
After your mother died,
he was sad all the time,

899
00:58:45,253 --> 00:58:48,631
but before that, he was pretty funny.

900
00:58:49,674 --> 00:58:50,799
Really?

901
00:58:55,138 --> 00:58:57,389
Now when I see him with Shelly,

902
00:58:58,183 --> 00:59:00,433
sometimes he seems like the old Harry.

903
00:59:01,227 --> 00:59:02,852
My dad was funny?

904
00:59:04,813 --> 00:59:08,399
Well, he wasn't one of the Marx Brothers,
but he made me laugh.

905
00:59:12,279 --> 00:59:14,447
My uncle fought in the Korean War.

906
00:59:14,532 --> 00:59:16,741
He had a steel plate put in his head.

907
00:59:16,825 --> 00:59:19,202
Daddy said he didn't come back the same.

908
00:59:19,286 --> 00:59:23,748
One night we picked up a radio station
from Oklahoma in his teeth.

909
00:59:24,166 --> 00:59:25,917
It was really neat.

910
00:59:30,381 --> 00:59:33,091
- Can't you see it?
- What?

911
00:59:33,175 --> 00:59:35,677
- Can't you see it?
- No.

912
00:59:35,761 --> 00:59:36,761
It's there.

913
00:59:36,845 --> 00:59:39,472
Vada, there is no chicken bone
stuck in your throat.

914
00:59:40,849 --> 00:59:43,559
Dr. Welty, are you sure those are yours?

915
00:59:45,728 --> 00:59:49,982
So you fill it with water, like this,
and what have you got?

916
00:59:50,066 --> 00:59:51,275
A water gun.

917
00:59:51,359 --> 00:59:54,987
- Cool! Can I get one for Vada?
- Yes, yes.

918
00:59:55,947 --> 00:59:57,990
Thomas, let me ask you a question.

919
00:59:58,449 --> 01:00:01,118
Does Vada ever tell you
why she comes down here so much?

920
01:00:01,202 --> 01:00:02,411
'Cause she's dying.

921
01:00:02,620 --> 01:00:04,663
- Do you think she is?
- No.

922
01:00:05,206 --> 01:00:06,665
Why do you think she says that?

923
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:09,501
Because she gets scared
of all those dead people in her house.

924
01:00:09,586 --> 01:00:12,838
And you know that saying,
"Can't beat them, join them. "

925
01:00:12,922 --> 01:00:15,340
Well, if she's one of them,
she won't be as scared.

926
01:00:15,425 --> 01:00:16,925
You know what I think?

927
01:00:17,010 --> 01:00:19,886
I think Vada's very lucky
to have a friend like you.

928
01:00:20,513 --> 01:00:22,347
She's my best friend.

929
01:00:23,808 --> 01:00:25,726
Miss Vada, how are you feeling?

930
01:00:26,602 --> 01:00:28,352
As good as can be expected.

931
01:00:31,356 --> 01:00:32,648
Hey, Vada, guess what we got?

932
01:00:32,733 --> 01:00:34,191
- What?
- This.

933
01:00:34,276 --> 01:00:37,028
Hey, you! I'm going to get you!

934
01:00:37,696 --> 01:00:39,488
I'll get you!

935
01:00:39,573 --> 01:00:40,740
Give me that, you creep!

936
01:00:43,869 --> 01:00:45,161
I just got you.

937
01:00:45,412 --> 01:00:46,954
No, you didn't.

938
01:00:47,372 --> 01:00:49,624
- Whoa.
- What?

939
01:00:49,708 --> 01:00:51,917
- There's a beehive right there.
- So?

940
01:00:52,419 --> 01:00:53,794
Stand back.

941
01:00:56,048 --> 01:00:58,382
Are you crazy? You'll get stung.

942
01:00:58,759 --> 01:01:00,468
You're right. Let's knock it down.

943
01:01:00,552 --> 01:01:04,055
- What do you want it for, anyway?
- 'Cause they're neat.

944
01:01:11,604 --> 01:01:12,979
I got it.

945
01:01:14,398 --> 01:01:17,567
My mood ring. It fell off. I got to find it.

946
01:01:24,617 --> 01:01:26,826
They're alive! Run for your life!

947
01:01:39,840 --> 01:01:43,510
- Run faster! They're after us!
- I am running faster!

948
01:01:44,303 --> 01:01:45,929
- Hurry!
- Jump in the water!

949
01:01:46,347 --> 01:01:48,973
- But I have my clothes on!
- Do it!

950
01:02:03,697 --> 01:02:06,490
- Vada, is that you?
- Yes.

951
01:02:06,574 --> 01:02:09,326
Hey, guess what.
We're going to the carnival tonight.

952
01:02:09,411 --> 01:02:11,286
Be ready to go in 10 minutes.

953
01:02:11,913 --> 01:02:13,622
Shelly's coming with us.

954
01:02:24,384 --> 01:02:28,220
- So, Vada, what's your favorite ride?
- I like the freak show.

955
01:02:28,680 --> 01:02:30,055
I know, I know.

956
01:02:30,140 --> 01:02:32,182
Let's go on
the sit-on-the-bench-and-rest ride.

957
01:02:33,768 --> 01:02:36,936
I don't think that the roller coaster agreed
with your dad's stomach.

958
01:02:37,020 --> 01:02:39,063
You know, Vada,
you have to watch what you eat here.

959
01:02:39,148 --> 01:02:42,233
I remember once I went to a carnival
with my cousins, David and Frank,

960
01:02:42,317 --> 01:02:43,735
and they both ate hot dogs

961
01:02:43,819 --> 01:02:45,737
and the next day
they came down with nephritis.

962
01:02:45,821 --> 01:02:48,030
Nephritis is a kidney disease.

963
01:02:48,532 --> 01:02:51,033
- You don't get it from hot dogs.
- Well, I'm no doctor.

964
01:02:51,118 --> 01:02:53,745
All I know is, the next day
they had really high fevers

965
01:02:53,829 --> 01:02:55,955
and their faces got very fat.

966
01:02:56,373 --> 01:02:59,500
They baffled medical science.
They were in a magazine.

967
01:03:00,711 --> 01:03:02,044
They were!

968
01:03:02,129 --> 01:03:04,964
Popular Mechanics... No, Popular Science.

969
01:03:05,507 --> 01:03:07,175
I don't know. It was Popular.

970
01:03:07,634 --> 01:03:12,263
- Look, they're trying to hit that poor
thing. - Watch you don't knock out a fish.

971
01:03:12,347 --> 01:03:13,848
Just arc it.

972
01:03:17,269 --> 01:03:19,187
I don't know which ball's mine.

973
01:03:19,563 --> 01:03:22,564
- I won! I won!
- Great!

974
01:03:22,648 --> 01:03:25,150
We have a winner. There you go, little girl.

975
01:03:25,234 --> 01:03:26,568
See how easy it is, folks.

976
01:03:26,652 --> 01:03:29,780
Vada, that's a gorgeous goldfish.

977
01:03:31,032 --> 01:03:32,491
Where did you get that ring?

978
01:03:35,453 --> 01:03:36,995
Did you win it?

979
01:03:43,628 --> 01:03:45,212
Vada, we have something to tell you.

980
01:03:47,590 --> 01:03:48,757
Harry?

981
01:03:52,136 --> 01:03:53,845
Vada, we have some good news.

982
01:03:54,722 --> 01:03:56,097
Shelly and I are getting married.

983
01:03:59,101 --> 01:04:00,519
My fish!

984
01:04:04,189 --> 01:04:07,149
We're having the wedding
sometime near the end of the summer.

985
01:04:07,484 --> 01:04:09,610
You'll be okay, little fish.

986
01:04:09,736 --> 01:04:10,861
Vada,

987
01:04:12,656 --> 01:04:14,698
would you like us
to get you another goldfish?

988
01:04:15,492 --> 01:04:16,534
No.

989
01:04:17,118 --> 01:04:18,118
He's fine.

990
01:04:19,246 --> 01:04:21,789
Fish are very resilient animals, you know.

991
01:04:23,250 --> 01:04:25,459
Don't worry. I won't get another fish.

992
01:04:29,297 --> 01:04:31,966
The bumper car! The bumper car!

993
01:04:32,050 --> 01:04:36,178
For just 50 cents,
a half dollar, five dimes, ten nickels,

994
01:04:36,263 --> 01:04:40,307
we have a ride that's guaranteed
to rearrange all of your internal organs.

995
01:04:40,433 --> 01:04:44,478
Don't pass me by!
That's the bumper car ride!

996
01:04:44,563 --> 01:04:45,938
Bumper cars!

997
01:04:46,022 --> 01:04:48,982
You can't go to a carnival
and not ride the bumper cars.

998
01:04:49,066 --> 01:04:50,984
I'd fall asleep at the wheel.

999
01:04:51,068 --> 01:04:55,113
- I'll ride on the bumper cars with you.
- Great, Vada, come on.

1000
01:04:59,994 --> 01:05:02,453
Two. I got the blue one!

1001
01:05:02,705 --> 01:05:04,372
- No.
- Yes.

1002
01:05:06,709 --> 01:05:08,835
I'm going to come get you.

1003
01:05:16,635 --> 01:05:18,469
Vada, keep your hands on the wheel.

1004
01:05:57,216 --> 01:05:58,842
Careful, Vada. Careful.

1005
01:06:00,094 --> 01:06:01,720
Shelly, look out!

1006
01:06:32,709 --> 01:06:35,252
- Hi, Vada.
- Hi, can Thomas J. come out?

1007
01:06:35,337 --> 01:06:36,963
Sure, come on in.

1008
01:06:39,841 --> 01:06:42,343
- Hi, Vada.
- Hi. Want to ride bikes?

1009
01:06:42,427 --> 01:06:43,636
Sure.

1010
01:06:44,846 --> 01:06:46,681
- Did you make your bed?
- Yes.

1011
01:06:47,140 --> 01:06:49,058
- You're sure?
- It's made.

1012
01:06:49,142 --> 01:06:52,061
Come here. You've got a milk mustache.

1013
01:06:55,315 --> 01:06:56,523
Come on, let's go.

1014
01:06:57,149 --> 01:06:59,859
- Bye, Mrs. Sennett.
- Bye, Ma.

1015
01:06:59,944 --> 01:07:01,486
Have fun, kids.

1016
01:07:04,031 --> 01:07:07,450
- I'm running away.
- Where you running to?

1017
01:07:08,577 --> 01:07:09,911
California.

1018
01:07:09,996 --> 01:07:12,455
Going to Hollywood
to live with The Brady Bunch.

1019
01:07:12,540 --> 01:07:15,500
- I want to live with them, too.
- No, you can't.

1020
01:07:15,584 --> 01:07:16,918
They have enough kids.

1021
01:07:17,003 --> 01:07:19,170
You'll have to live with
The Partridge Family.

1022
01:07:20,172 --> 01:07:21,381
Really?

1023
01:07:36,939 --> 01:07:38,314
That's it.

1024
01:07:48,908 --> 01:07:51,285
- Get up.
- I'm tired of running away.

1025
01:07:51,703 --> 01:07:54,621
Besides, we passed
this place two times already.

1026
01:07:54,706 --> 01:07:56,040
We're not getting nowhere.

1027
01:07:59,002 --> 01:08:00,294
So, why are you running away?

1028
01:08:01,713 --> 01:08:05,841
- My dad gave Shelly a ring.
- Wow! Was it a decoder ring?

1029
01:08:06,468 --> 01:08:10,012
You're such a retard.
It was an engagement ring.

1030
01:08:10,305 --> 01:08:11,972
They're getting married?

1031
01:08:12,515 --> 01:08:13,849
So now you have a mother.

1032
01:08:14,267 --> 01:08:15,350
I don't like her.

1033
01:08:15,894 --> 01:08:17,561
I do. She's real funny.

1034
01:08:18,813 --> 01:08:20,814
He likes her better than me.

1035
01:08:26,987 --> 01:08:30,698
- I'm hungry. I can't last any longer.
- Then go home, baby.

1036
01:08:30,991 --> 01:08:33,367
I have to, anyway. My mom will be worried.

1037
01:08:33,827 --> 01:08:35,828
Leave then. Some friend you are.

1038
01:08:36,330 --> 01:08:38,331
You can come to my house for dinner.

1039
01:08:39,333 --> 01:08:40,625
No, I'm hiding out.

1040
01:08:41,418 --> 01:08:42,919
Okay, see you.

1041
01:09:41,060 --> 01:09:42,769
Are the gentlemen going to stay or not?

1042
01:09:45,898 --> 01:09:47,983
Perhaps you didn't hear what I said,
Mr. Deeds.

1043
01:09:48,818 --> 01:09:52,486
The whole Circle fortune goes to you.
$20 million.

1044
01:09:52,571 --> 01:09:53,988
Oh, yes, I heard you all right.

1045
01:09:54,239 --> 01:09:56,073
Twenty million,
that's quite a lot, isn't it?

1046
01:09:56,575 --> 01:09:58,033
It will do in a pinch.

1047
01:09:58,118 --> 01:10:01,579
I wonder why he left me all that money?
I don't need it.

1048
01:10:03,665 --> 01:10:05,207
In social studies we learned some people

1049
01:10:05,292 --> 01:10:08,544
stole the Lindbergh baby
right out of his house.

1050
01:10:08,628 --> 01:10:11,714
I think I'll sleep
with my window open tonight.

1051
01:10:15,802 --> 01:10:17,178
Oh, my God!

1052
01:10:17,929 --> 01:10:19,138
Daddy!

1053
01:10:20,140 --> 01:10:21,599
Daddy! Daddy!

1054
01:10:23,560 --> 01:10:24,561
Daddy!

1055
01:10:25,020 --> 01:10:26,187
Daddy!

1056
01:10:27,564 --> 01:10:29,857
- Daddy!
- Vada, what's the matter?

1057
01:10:31,234 --> 01:10:32,234
Where's Daddy?

1058
01:10:32,360 --> 01:10:34,694
- He just left. What's wrong?
- I'm hemorrhaging.

1059
01:10:34,778 --> 01:10:36,070
What do you mean, you're hemorrhaging?

1060
01:10:36,155 --> 01:10:40,658
- I don't want or need your help.
- Vada, did this happen in the bathroom?

1061
01:10:42,453 --> 01:10:44,579
- How old are you?
- I'm 11 and a half.

1062
01:10:45,581 --> 01:10:46,623
It's okay.

1063
01:10:47,041 --> 01:10:48,791
Come on upstairs.
We have to have a little talk.

1064
01:10:52,463 --> 01:10:54,464
My mommy and daddy did that?

1065
01:10:55,049 --> 01:10:57,342
Actually, a very beautiful thing.

1066
01:10:59,011 --> 01:11:00,595
And look, there wouldn't have been a Vada.

1067
01:11:01,263 --> 01:11:02,680
I think it should be outlawed.

1068
01:11:03,224 --> 01:11:04,807
Believe me, someday you'll feel differently.

1069
01:11:06,852 --> 01:11:09,479
That's probably Thomas J.
I don't want to see him.

1070
01:11:11,440 --> 01:11:12,941
It's not fair.

1071
01:11:13,317 --> 01:11:15,318
Nothing happens to boys.

1072
01:11:19,364 --> 01:11:21,406
Hi, Vada. Can you come out?

1073
01:11:22,408 --> 01:11:23,575
I don't know.

1074
01:11:23,660 --> 01:11:26,703
Please. It's real hot.
Maybe we can go swimming.

1075
01:11:28,831 --> 01:11:31,250
No. Get out of here.

1076
01:11:32,627 --> 01:11:35,587
And don't come back
for five to seven days!

1077
01:11:53,273 --> 01:11:56,858
Gramoo, I'm going to the bathroom.
I'll be right back.

1078
01:11:58,987 --> 01:12:00,319
Stay here.

1079
01:12:58,095 --> 01:13:00,620
<i>It's quarter to three</i>

1080
01:13:01,365 --> 01:13:03,890
<i>There's no one in the place</i>

1081
01:13:04,001 --> 01:13:06,561
<i>Just you and me</i>

1082
01:13:06,670 --> 01:13:09,662
<i>So set them up, Joe</i>

1083
01:13:09,773 --> 01:13:14,005
<i>I've got a little story
you ought to know</i>

1084
01:13:14,978 --> 01:13:17,276
<i>We're coming, my friend</i>

1085
01:13:18,549 --> 01:13:22,986
<i>- To the end of brief episode
- I'm so sorry.</i>

1086
01:13:23,043 --> 01:13:27,009
<i>- All right, Ma. It's okay.
- So make it one for my baby</i>

1087
01:13:27,657 --> 01:13:31,684
<i>- And one more for the road
- Very, very sorry.</i>

1088
01:13:36,164 --> 01:13:37,623
Now what were you thinking, huh?

1089
01:13:38,792 --> 01:13:40,876
It's your responsibility to watch her!

1090
01:13:40,960 --> 01:13:44,421
Do you have any idea how upset
those people are in there?

1091
01:13:58,269 --> 01:14:00,813
Why do you think people
want to get married?

1092
01:14:01,314 --> 01:14:03,482
When you get older, you just have to.

1093
01:14:04,984 --> 01:14:06,944
I'm going to marry Mr. Bixler.

1094
01:14:07,570 --> 01:14:09,946
You can't marry a teacher.
It's against the law.

1095
01:14:10,447 --> 01:14:12,407
- It is not.
- Yes, it is.

1096
01:14:12,491 --> 01:14:15,326
'Cause then he'll give you
all A's and it won't be fair.

1097
01:14:15,828 --> 01:14:17,120
Not true.

1098
01:14:21,083 --> 01:14:22,166
Have you ever kissed anyone?

1099
01:14:23,836 --> 01:14:25,336
Like they do on TV?

1100
01:14:26,839 --> 01:14:27,839
No.

1101
01:14:30,801 --> 01:14:33,928
Well, maybe we should,
just to see what's the big deal.

1102
01:14:35,180 --> 01:14:36,722
But I don't know how.

1103
01:14:37,307 --> 01:14:39,684
Here, practice on your arm like this.

1104
01:14:40,519 --> 01:14:41,769
Like this?

1105
01:14:45,232 --> 01:14:46,899
Okay, enough practice.

1106
01:14:47,568 --> 01:14:48,734
Close your eyes.

1107
01:14:49,445 --> 01:14:50,695
Then I won't be able to see anything.

1108
01:14:51,363 --> 01:14:53,780
- Just do it.
- Okay, okay.

1109
01:14:57,535 --> 01:14:59,369
Okay, on the count of three.

1110
01:15:00,872 --> 01:15:02,038
One.

1111
01:15:02,957 --> 01:15:04,082
Two.

1112
01:15:04,167 --> 01:15:05,542
Two and a half.

1113
01:15:06,043 --> 01:15:07,377
Three.

1114
01:15:15,720 --> 01:15:17,679
Say something. It's too quiet.

1115
01:15:21,434 --> 01:15:22,642
Just hurry.

1116
01:15:24,395 --> 01:15:28,815
"I pledge allegiance to the flag
of the United States of America

1117
01:15:29,233 --> 01:15:31,401
- "and to the Republic for which it stands.
- "For which it stands.

1118
01:15:31,611 --> 01:15:34,654
- "One nation under God, indivisible.
- "One nation under God, indivisible,

1119
01:15:34,739 --> 01:15:37,948
- "with liberty and justice for all. "
- "with liberty and justice for all. "

1120
01:15:58,929 --> 01:16:01,972
- You better not tell anyone.
- You better not either.

1121
01:16:02,057 --> 01:16:05,518
- Well, let's spit on it.
- Okay.

1122
01:16:07,270 --> 01:16:09,897
- See you tomorrow.
- Okay, see you.

1123
01:16:10,398 --> 01:16:11,482
Vada?

1124
01:16:12,317 --> 01:16:13,442
What?

1125
01:16:14,444 --> 01:16:15,819
Would you think of me?

1126
01:16:16,279 --> 01:16:17,571
For what?

1127
01:16:18,698 --> 01:16:21,241
If you don't get to marry Mr. Bixler.

1128
01:16:23,327 --> 01:16:24,577
I guess.

1129
01:17:12,709 --> 01:17:13,792
Yes.

1130
01:17:22,844 --> 01:17:23,927
No.

1131
01:17:24,178 --> 01:17:25,470
God, no.

1132
01:17:27,390 --> 01:17:28,682
Get away.

1133
01:17:29,517 --> 01:17:30,559
Get away!

1134
01:18:14,061 --> 01:18:15,311
Hi, Vada.

1135
01:18:15,437 --> 01:18:16,687
Hi.

1136
01:18:19,983 --> 01:18:21,150
What are you doing?

1137
01:18:21,652 --> 01:18:22,902
Feeding my fish.

1138
01:18:27,532 --> 01:18:30,492
- Is that the fish you won at the carnival?
- Yes.

1139
01:18:33,579 --> 01:18:35,246
He's getting big.

1140
01:18:39,877 --> 01:18:42,337
Vada, come here and sit down for a minute.

1141
01:18:46,425 --> 01:18:50,512
Vada, something happened
to Thomas J. last night.

1142
01:18:52,598 --> 01:18:54,724
He stepped on a beehive.

1143
01:18:55,393 --> 01:18:57,811
I told him not to tease those bees.

1144
01:18:58,062 --> 01:18:59,229
Did he get stung?

1145
01:19:03,234 --> 01:19:05,485
Maybe I should go over and yell at him.

1146
01:19:07,780 --> 01:19:10,448
No, sweetheart. You can't.

1147
01:19:13,451 --> 01:19:14,702
Why not?

1148
01:19:18,373 --> 01:19:19,998
He was allergic to bees.

1149
01:19:22,043 --> 01:19:23,794
He's okay, isn't he?

1150
01:19:26,506 --> 01:19:28,590
There were just too many of them.

1151
01:19:46,443 --> 01:19:47,776
Dr. Welty!

1152
01:19:49,154 --> 01:19:50,154
Dr. Welty!

1153
01:19:50,238 --> 01:19:52,865
Vada, what's wrong, sweetheart?

1154
01:19:52,949 --> 01:19:56,159
- I can't breathe. I'm suffocating.
- Wait, relax now.

1155
01:19:56,243 --> 01:19:57,410
Let me look. It's okay.

1156
01:19:57,494 --> 01:20:00,496
Up here, we'll have a look. That's a girl.

1157
01:20:00,873 --> 01:20:03,666
It hurts. It hurts so bad.

1158
01:20:03,792 --> 01:20:07,003
- Make it stop.
- What hurts, Vada?

1159
01:20:07,379 --> 01:20:09,005
The bee stings!

1160
01:20:09,089 --> 01:20:10,673
I can't breathe.

1161
01:20:36,742 --> 01:20:37,909
Vada?

1162
01:20:39,577 --> 01:20:43,121
I'm leaving some food for you by the door
in case you get hungry.

1163
01:20:49,545 --> 01:20:51,838
- Hi.
- Hi. Is Vada home?

1164
01:20:52,298 --> 01:20:56,885
Yes, she is, but she's very upset
so she's not seeing anyone.

1165
01:20:57,386 --> 01:21:00,055
I'm Judy. I go to school with her.

1166
01:21:00,139 --> 01:21:02,599
I wanted to tell her I'm
sorry about Thomas J.

1167
01:21:03,935 --> 01:21:05,894
Well, maybe she'll feel better
in a couple days.

1168
01:21:06,145 --> 01:21:07,229
Will you tell her I came by?

1169
01:21:08,231 --> 01:21:09,856
- Sure.
- Thank you.

1170
01:21:09,941 --> 01:21:11,900
- Bye.
- Bye.

1171
01:21:19,951 --> 01:21:21,992
- Hi, Harry.
- Hi, Reverend Moss.

1172
01:21:22,077 --> 01:21:25,538
The Sennett's want to thank you
for taking care of things so quickly.

1173
01:21:36,216 --> 01:21:37,299
Vada?

1174
01:21:38,009 --> 01:21:39,969
I see you took your tray in.

1175
01:21:41,096 --> 01:21:43,597
Maybe you should come down
for the funeral.

1176
01:21:43,932 --> 01:21:45,683
Sometimes it helps.

1177
01:21:46,977 --> 01:21:48,185
Vada?

1178
01:21:56,695 --> 01:21:58,445
She won't come out.

1179
01:21:59,823 --> 01:22:01,574
It's been a whole day.

1180
01:22:03,285 --> 01:22:05,285
You have to do something, Harry.

1181
01:22:05,995 --> 01:22:07,537
The funeral's starting.

1182
01:22:07,621 --> 01:22:10,331
Open your eyes. She's 11 years old.

1183
01:22:11,292 --> 01:22:13,042
Her only friend in the world is dead.

1184
01:22:13,127 --> 01:22:15,295
I know that, but what do you want from me?

1185
01:22:15,504 --> 01:22:17,255
Stop hiding, Harry.

1186
01:22:18,299 --> 01:22:19,424
You run, Harry.

1187
01:22:20,551 --> 01:22:21,968
When I first came here,

1188
01:22:22,261 --> 01:22:25,972
the idea of working with dead people
didn't exactly thrill me.

1189
01:22:27,433 --> 01:22:29,851
But when I saw a family lived here,

1190
01:22:31,061 --> 01:22:32,478
I thought,

1191
01:22:33,689 --> 01:22:35,899
"If I'm living without a family,

1192
01:22:36,609 --> 01:22:38,276
"at least I can work with one.

1193
01:22:39,570 --> 01:22:42,155
"And maybe once in a while
be invited in for supper. "

1194
01:22:42,323 --> 01:22:43,252
Yeah.

1195
01:22:43,595 --> 01:22:46,068
And when those suppers are disrupted
because there's a car crash,

1196
01:22:46,157 --> 01:22:48,501
or there's a fire,
or a little boy steps on a beehive.

1197
01:22:48,536 --> 01:22:52,122
I'm not asking you
to stop feeling for those people.

1198
01:22:54,667 --> 01:22:56,668
But life isn't just death, Harry.

1199
01:22:59,005 --> 01:23:00,464
Don't ignore the living.

1200
01:23:02,383 --> 01:23:04,384
Especially your daughter.

1201
01:23:07,722 --> 01:23:10,515
Excuse me, Harry, Shelly,
the minister's about to begin.

1202
01:23:11,184 --> 01:23:12,851
Thank you, Arthur.

1203
01:23:27,533 --> 01:23:31,411
We are here to honor Thomas James Sennett.

1204
01:23:32,537 --> 01:23:37,291
He was born May 7, 1961
in Madison, Pennsylvania.

1205
01:23:37,793 --> 01:23:41,879
He is survived by his loving parents,
Charles and Susan Sennett,

1206
01:23:42,214 --> 01:23:45,466
his grandparents,
William and Gloria Sennett,

1207
01:23:45,550 --> 01:23:47,176
and Gerald and Marjorie Finn,

1208
01:23:47,260 --> 01:23:49,929
and many relatives, friends and schoolmates.

1209
01:23:51,932 --> 01:23:55,226
The interment will follow
at Madison Memorial Park.

1210
01:23:56,061 --> 01:23:59,814
The family has asked me to say a few words
before we proceed to the cemetery.

1211
01:24:02,401 --> 01:24:03,985
No words I could say

1212
01:24:04,069 --> 01:24:07,905
would begin to express
the loss and grief we feel.

1213
01:24:09,491 --> 01:24:13,828
One word that keeps ringing
in my ear is "why?"

1214
01:24:15,037 --> 01:24:17,622
Why would God choose
to take this little boy from us?

1215
01:24:19,875 --> 01:24:22,711
Well, I can't give you
an answer to that question,

1216
01:24:22,795 --> 01:24:26,548
but I can tell you
that God has chosen Thomas J.

1217
01:24:26,632 --> 01:24:28,842
for some very special reason.

1218
01:24:30,511 --> 01:24:34,431
We must find solace
in knowing that Thomas J. is in God's care.

1219
01:24:35,099 --> 01:24:39,102
In that place,
there is no sorrow or suffering.

1220
01:24:40,187 --> 01:24:44,315
The lion lies with the lamb.
The day is not divided.

1221
01:24:45,109 --> 01:24:47,569
I'd like to read a passage from the Bible.

1222
01:24:49,447 --> 01:24:51,948
This is Matthew 19:13.

1223
01:24:53,075 --> 01:24:55,869
"At one point, children were brought to him

1224
01:24:55,953 --> 01:24:58,954
"that he might lay his hands
on them and pray.

1225
01:24:59,289 --> 01:25:01,248
"The disciples began to chastise them.

1226
01:25:02,042 --> 01:25:05,461
"But Jesus said,
'Let the children come to me.

1227
01:25:06,796 --> 01:25:08,672
"Do not hinder them.

1228
01:25:08,757 --> 01:25:12,092
"The kingdom of God
belongs to such as these. "

1229
01:25:13,219 --> 01:25:15,179
"And he laid his hands on their heads

1230
01:25:16,723 --> 01:25:18,432
"before he left that place. "

1231
01:25:19,225 --> 01:25:21,393
Let us pray in silence.

1232
01:25:23,146 --> 01:25:25,773
You want to go tree-climbing, Thomas J?

1233
01:25:26,107 --> 01:25:27,316
His face hurts.

1234
01:25:27,817 --> 01:25:30,652
And where is his glasses?
He can't see without his glasses.

1235
01:25:32,363 --> 01:25:35,699
Put his glasses on. Put on his glasses.

1236
01:25:38,328 --> 01:25:39,912
He was going to be an acrobat.

1237
01:25:39,996 --> 01:25:43,498
- He's gone, sweetheart. He's gone.
- Get away from me!

1238
01:25:47,961 --> 01:25:49,378
Vada, wait!

1239
01:25:49,463 --> 01:25:50,671
Vada!

1240
01:25:52,508 --> 01:25:53,716
Vada!

1241
01:26:05,771 --> 01:26:08,439
Vada, I was just on my way to your house.

1242
01:26:08,524 --> 01:26:10,274
Are you all right?

1243
01:26:10,359 --> 01:26:11,692
I'm so sorry about Thomas J.

1244
01:26:13,737 --> 01:26:15,863
Okay, we don't have to talk about him.

1245
01:26:16,990 --> 01:26:19,408
Vada, Vada, we don't have to talk about him.
It's okay.

1246
01:26:19,493 --> 01:26:20,785
We won't talk about him.

1247
01:26:20,869 --> 01:26:24,122
Justin and Ronda say
that I should tell people what I feel.

1248
01:26:25,456 --> 01:26:27,833
Come here, sit down. Sit down over here.

1249
01:26:30,461 --> 01:26:31,920
Mr. Bixler...

1250
01:26:33,548 --> 01:26:34,881
I love you.

1251
01:26:35,675 --> 01:26:36,716
Vada...

1252
01:26:37,176 --> 01:26:39,678
I love you like my dad loves Shelly.

1253
01:26:40,721 --> 01:26:42,139
I want to live here.

1254
01:26:45,810 --> 01:26:47,561
I think your dad would miss you.

1255
01:26:47,645 --> 01:26:49,521
No, he wouldn't.

1256
01:26:49,605 --> 01:26:51,148
I can't go home.

1257
01:26:51,232 --> 01:26:54,985
Jake, I'll be ready in a second.
I can't seem to find my other earring.

1258
01:26:56,154 --> 01:26:57,654
Suzanne, this is Vada.

1259
01:26:57,738 --> 01:27:00,157
Vada, hi.

1260
01:27:00,950 --> 01:27:02,159
I'm really sorry.

1261
01:27:02,243 --> 01:27:04,703
- Could you just give us a minute?
- Yeah.

1262
01:27:08,248 --> 01:27:09,540
Who's that?

1263
01:27:10,959 --> 01:27:12,501
That's Suzanne.

1264
01:27:18,258 --> 01:27:20,509
She and I are going to be married this fall.

1265
01:27:20,594 --> 01:27:21,552
No.

1266
01:27:21,636 --> 01:27:24,180
I was going to bring her to class next week.

1267
01:27:24,598 --> 01:27:26,473
I want her to hear your poem.

1268
01:27:27,809 --> 01:27:29,226
Vada.

1269
01:27:29,311 --> 01:27:31,520
Please, honey.
I cared for him, too. Vada, please.

1270
01:27:31,605 --> 01:27:33,230
Get away from me.

1271
01:27:33,732 --> 01:27:34,815
Vada!

1272
01:27:36,735 --> 01:27:38,777
Vada, sweetheart, don't...

1273
01:28:11,268 --> 01:28:14,229
Why do you think
people want to get married?

1274
01:28:14,313 --> 01:28:17,023
When you get older, you just have to.

1275
01:28:21,737 --> 01:28:23,738
Who's that with your dad?

1276
01:28:24,406 --> 01:28:26,282
That's my mother.

1277
01:28:28,494 --> 01:28:31,496
I'm going to be an acrobat when I grow up.

1278
01:28:32,164 --> 01:28:33,289
Vada?

1279
01:28:34,166 --> 01:28:35,999
Would you think of me?

1280
01:28:36,751 --> 01:28:39,294
If you don't get to marry Mr. Bixler.

1281
01:28:44,050 --> 01:28:46,677
Now we're blood brothers for life.

1282
01:29:04,862 --> 01:29:06,697
Shelly, I'm sorry,
but we haven't found her yet.

1283
01:29:06,781 --> 01:29:08,824
It's dark. She can't be alone in the dark.

1284
01:29:08,908 --> 01:29:10,951
- We'll keep looking.
- We've been looking since this morning.

1285
01:29:11,035 --> 01:29:14,496
- Her teacher called and he said...
- I know, I know. You told us.

1286
01:29:15,498 --> 01:29:16,665
Vada?

1287
01:29:20,877 --> 01:29:22,336
Are you okay?

1288
01:29:23,088 --> 01:29:24,338
Oh, God.

1289
01:29:26,300 --> 01:29:29,552
I should have told Thomas J.
that he was my best friend.

1290
01:29:31,138 --> 01:29:32,763
I'm sure he knew.

1291
01:29:42,107 --> 01:29:43,274
Shelly.

1292
01:29:44,693 --> 01:29:49,739
I stole some money from your cookie jar
to pay for the writing class.

1293
01:29:53,410 --> 01:29:56,287
- It's okay, sweetheart.
- I'll pay you back.

1294
01:29:56,371 --> 01:29:59,623
Besides, I don't think
I'll ever go to class again.

1295
01:30:02,251 --> 01:30:06,087
I'll tell you what.
You dedicate your first book to me.

1296
01:30:06,422 --> 01:30:08,089
I'll forget the whole thing.

1297
01:30:08,758 --> 01:30:11,718
- I will. I promise.
- Okay. Get into bed.

1298
01:30:34,075 --> 01:30:35,658
- Good night.
- Good night.

1299
01:30:54,803 --> 01:30:55,969
She's here.

1300
01:31:14,364 --> 01:31:16,407
Did I kill my mother?

1301
01:31:16,491 --> 01:31:17,616
What?

1302
01:31:20,912 --> 01:31:24,415
The bees killed Thomas J.
and I killed my mother.

1303
01:31:24,499 --> 01:31:25,707
No, no.

1304
01:31:34,633 --> 01:31:37,176
Now, sweetie, that wasn't your fault.

1305
01:31:38,512 --> 01:31:43,099
Things like that aren't anybody's fault.
It just happened.

1306
01:31:48,021 --> 01:31:49,522
I found this.

1307
01:31:55,320 --> 01:31:57,238
I forgot about that picture.

1308
01:31:57,322 --> 01:32:00,366
- Where did you find it?
- In the garage.

1309
01:32:02,202 --> 01:32:04,370
That little Chevy
was your mother's favorite car.

1310
01:32:06,290 --> 01:32:07,874
What was my mama like?

1311
01:32:09,835 --> 01:32:11,334
She was pretty.

1312
01:32:12,211 --> 01:32:13,503
And kind.

1313
01:32:13,963 --> 01:32:15,630
And she had your eyes.

1314
01:32:18,926 --> 01:32:21,052
Boy, did she love to laugh.

1315
01:32:23,723 --> 01:32:26,057
Sometimes when you laugh,
you sound just like her.

1316
01:32:26,726 --> 01:32:27,893
Really?

1317
01:32:29,770 --> 01:32:33,440
You know what your mother did when she
found out she was going to have you?

1318
01:32:34,734 --> 01:32:37,444
She came home
and painted this whole room pink.

1319
01:32:39,363 --> 01:32:41,323
She was so sure she
would have a little girl.

1320
01:32:42,074 --> 01:32:43,700
Do you miss her?

1321
01:32:45,828 --> 01:32:46,995
Yes.

1322
01:32:47,079 --> 01:32:50,165
I did, very much, for a long time.

1323
01:32:52,418 --> 01:32:56,837
And even now I get a little sad
when I think about a pretty flower

1324
01:32:56,922 --> 01:33:00,341
or a beautiful sunset
that your mother would have liked.

1325
01:33:00,425 --> 01:33:04,762
I think every time I see or climb a tree
I'll think of Thomas J.

1326
01:33:06,348 --> 01:33:07,765
That's good.

1327
01:33:08,600 --> 01:33:10,518
Memories are good, sweetheart.

1328
01:33:12,020 --> 01:33:13,270
Vada, I'm...

1329
01:33:13,647 --> 01:33:14,980
I'm sorry.

1330
01:33:16,274 --> 01:33:19,568
I was trying to keep it from you.

1331
01:33:22,113 --> 01:33:23,739
I just couldn't.

1332
01:33:28,245 --> 01:33:31,497
You're a good girl. I want you to be happy.

1333
01:33:32,290 --> 01:33:34,208
Don't be an old grump like me.

1334
01:33:42,007 --> 01:33:43,925
See you in the morning.

1335
01:33:47,429 --> 01:33:48,596
Daddy?

1336
01:33:50,683 --> 01:33:52,976
It's not so bad to be like you.

1337
01:34:19,253 --> 01:34:21,545
Mrs. Sennett, how are you doing?

1338
01:34:23,631 --> 01:34:25,924
Some days I think I'll be okay.

1339
01:34:26,342 --> 01:34:31,555
Others... Well, I have
to force myself even to get out of bed.

1340
01:34:32,557 --> 01:34:34,099
I know it's crazy,

1341
01:34:34,183 --> 01:34:36,435
but sometimes I think
he's just away at summer camp.

1342
01:34:38,021 --> 01:34:39,396
How's Vada?

1343
01:34:39,856 --> 01:34:43,233
She's doing much better. She's just inside.

1344
01:34:43,818 --> 01:34:44,901
Vada!

1345
01:34:48,990 --> 01:34:51,700
- Mrs. Sennett.
- Vada.

1346
01:34:55,872 --> 01:34:58,248
I've been wanting to come over to see you.

1347
01:35:01,878 --> 01:35:03,879
Thomas J. had this on him.

1348
01:35:05,380 --> 01:35:07,340
I thought you might like to have it.

1349
01:35:19,186 --> 01:35:21,646
You were such a good friend to him.

1350
01:35:22,689 --> 01:35:24,607
I hope you'll still come by and visit me.

1351
01:35:25,025 --> 01:35:27,735
I will. I promise.

1352
01:35:35,077 --> 01:35:36,160
Mrs. Sennett,

1353
01:35:38,455 --> 01:35:40,665
Thomas J. will be all right.

1354
01:35:40,749 --> 01:35:43,084
My mother will take care of him.

1355
01:35:46,380 --> 01:35:48,088
Thank you, Vada.

1356
01:35:57,264 --> 01:35:59,683
"Encased in talent, like a uniform

1357
01:36:00,768 --> 01:36:03,353
"The rank of every poet is well known

1358
01:36:05,022 --> 01:36:07,607
"They can amaze us like a thunderstorm

1359
01:36:09,068 --> 01:36:12,278
"Or die so young

1360
01:36:12,363 --> 01:36:14,322
"Or live for years alone. "

1361
01:36:17,952 --> 01:36:20,412
My advice to you on our last class,

1362
01:36:22,957 --> 01:36:24,624
be a thunderstorm.

1363
01:36:26,544 --> 01:36:28,586
What exactly do you mean by that?

1364
01:36:31,214 --> 01:36:32,464
I mean,

1365
01:36:33,341 --> 01:36:34,758
be dangerous,

1366
01:36:36,720 --> 01:36:38,470
and unpredictable,

1367
01:36:39,973 --> 01:36:41,932
and make a lot of noise.

1368
01:36:46,146 --> 01:36:47,229
Vada.

1369
01:36:50,316 --> 01:36:51,483
Hey!

1370
01:36:51,776 --> 01:36:53,110
We missed you, man.

1371
01:36:53,194 --> 01:36:54,695
Give me a hug.

1372
01:36:59,325 --> 01:37:01,660
I was hoping you'd stop by today.

1373
01:37:06,541 --> 01:37:10,043
Can't stay. I just came to read my poem.

1374
01:37:10,670 --> 01:37:12,504
We'd love to hear it.

1375
01:37:18,844 --> 01:37:21,179
"Weeping willow
with your tears running down

1376
01:37:22,055 --> 01:37:24,474
"Why do you always weep and frown?

1377
01:37:25,058 --> 01:37:27,518
"Is it because he left you one day?

1378
01:37:28,103 --> 01:37:30,438
"Is it because he could not stay?

1379
01:37:32,024 --> 01:37:34,358
"On your branches he would swing

1380
01:37:34,526 --> 01:37:37,361
"Do you long for the happiness
that day would bring?

1381
01:37:38,238 --> 01:37:40,573
"He found shelter in your shade

1382
01:37:41,575 --> 01:37:44,368
"We thought his laughter would never fade

1383
01:37:45,496 --> 01:37:47,830
"Weeping willow, stop your tears

1384
01:37:48,707 --> 01:37:51,542
"For there is something to calm your fears

1385
01:37:52,336 --> 01:37:55,254
"You think death
has ripped you forever apart

1386
01:37:56,548 --> 01:37:59,382
"But I know he'll always be in your heart. "

1387
01:38:09,393 --> 01:38:11,353
- Hi, Judy.
- Vada.

1388
01:38:12,063 --> 01:38:13,980
Things are a little better these days.

1389
01:38:14,065 --> 01:38:16,066
I finally swallowed that chicken bone.

1390
01:38:16,150 --> 01:38:18,985
Judy and I are going to be
in the same homeroom,

1391
01:38:19,070 --> 01:38:22,489
and the Republican Party
just renominated Mr. Nixon.


